4. Data Preprocessing

4.1 Checking for Data Accuracy

4.1.1 Create a new column called CarCompany from CarName variable

In this step, I clean and preprocess the data, handling any missing values or outliers, to ensure the accuracy of my subsequent analyses. - The first step was to get rid of the car_id column, because I deemed that this would not be necessary for my exploratory data analysis. From here, I created a column for the manufacturer of the car, which I called “CarCompany”. This was obtained by splitting the company name from the CarName column, using a space as delimiter and replacing the “CarName” variable as the “CarCompany” variable. After this, I also had to go through all the car company names because I noticed that there Ire plenty of spelling errors in the dataset. I then manually had to correct the spelling of all the manufacturers that were spelled wrong such as maxda, porscshe, toyouta, vokwagen, etc.

4.1.2 Factor the Categorical variables

Next, I converted categorical variables into factor variables with accurate labeling; these variables include CarCompany, symboling, fueltype, aspiration, doornumber, carbody, drivewheel, enginelocation, enginetype, cylindernumber, and fuelsystem. No missing values or duplicates were found during data inspection. I then used Mahalanobis, Leverage, and Cook’s distance to detect and remove outliers

#Factor the categorical variables

4.4 Removing outliers

4.4.1 Mahalanobis

#calculate the mahalanobis distances for each row in the data, excluding the categorical variables

mahal <- mahalanobis(car_accurate[,-c(1:8,14,15,17)],
                     colMeans(car_accurate[,-c(1:8,14,15,17)]),
                     cov(car_accurate[,-c(1:8,14,15,17)]))

#calculate the cutoff value by calculating the quantile of the  Chi-squared distribution based on the strict significance level of 0.001 and the degree of freedom as the number of variables/columns
cutmahal <- qchisq(1-.001, ncol(car_accurate[,-c(1:9,15,16,18)]))

badmahal <- as.numeric(mahal > cutmahal) ##note the direction of the > 
table(badmahal)
## badmahal
##   0   1 
## 196   9

4.4.2 Leverage

#To get the other outlier statistics, I have to use the regression model I wish to test. And in this case, I will use the lm() function with my regression formula.)
car_mod_1 <- lm(price ~ ., data = car_accurate)
k <- 24 ##number of IVs
leverage <- hatvalues(car_mod_1)
cutleverage <- (2*k+2) / nrow(car_accurate)
badleverage <- as.numeric(leverage > cutleverage)

cooks <- cooks.distance(car_mod_1)

## [1] "Kurtosis of car price:  6.11028130958224"

The first step in exploratory data analysis was to evaluate the dependent variable of price by creating a histogram and Normal Q-Q plot The car price varies in the range of 5118 and 36880.

From the histogram, I found that the price variable was extremely positively skewed which is confirmed by the value of skewness and kurtosis.

Skewness measure a degree of asymmetry of data distribution that deviates from the symmetrical normal distribution. The value of skewness at 1.726 shows that the data are extremely skewed.

Kurtosis measures the heaviness of a distribution’s tails relative to a normal distribution. Since the standard normal distribution has kurtosis of 3, the kurtosis value at 6.11 (excess kurtosis is at 3.11) indicating an extremely positive Kurtosis, or leptokurtic distribution. Positive kurtosis describes a heavier tails and more peaked distributed data

# Define function to calculate skewness and kurtosis
skew_kurt <- function(data, variable_name) {
  skew <- skewness(data[[variable_name]])
  kurt <- kurtosis(data[[variable_name]])

  print(paste("Skewness of", toTitleCase(variable_name), ":", skew))
  print(paste("Kurtosis of", toTitleCase(variable_name), ":", kurt))
}

6.2 Multiple Linear Regression Models’

In order to choose the best model, we experimented with four different multiple linear regression models. The first one we did predicted the price of a car based on all the other variables in the dataset. As we mentioned above however, there were a couple of variables that showed singularity. So our second model used all of the variables except for “citympg” and “compressionratio”. Although the second model was already much better than the first, we still wanted more accuracy in predicting the price. So for our third and fourth models, we removed the variables that we found had the highest p-values on top of the singularity variables mentioned above. Model 3 uses everything except for the previously mentioned variables and the “drivewheel” variable since it had a very high p-value. Model 4 does not take into consideration the three variables omitted in Model 3, and also excludes the “doornumber” variable since it again has a very high p-value.

6.2.1 Full model (24IVs)

In order to validate our model, we first had to split the dataset into two: 80% was used as the training set, and 20% was used as the testing set. The training set was then used to train the model that we chose, so that we could use it to predict our target variable of price in the test set. To test exactly how accurate our model was, we calculated the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) between the predicted and the actual values. MAE calculates the average of the absolute differences between predicted and actual values. It is less sensitive to outliers compared to MSE. RMSE is the square root of MSE which calculates the average of the squared differences between predicted and actual values and it is commonly used as it provides an interpretable metric in the same unit as the target variable. Like MSE, a lower RMSE is desired, indicating a better-performing model

To confirm that this model was the best one out of all four, we then compared it to the second best model - Model 3. We ran the same method for validating the model, and calculated the MSE and RMSE to see how accurate this one was at predicting the price. Comparing the two pairs of values, we saw that Model 4 had an RMSE of 1408.397 and an MSE of 1183.248, while Model 3 had an RMSE of 1409.061 and an MSE of 1184.13. This confirms our choice of Model 4 as the best predictor model, since it had a lower RMSE and MSE than the second best model, and thus every other model that was in contention.
